            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee> in <placeName>Phila.</placeName></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland,</placeName>
                <date>August 1st 5612</date> AM</p>
            <p>Dear sir:</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">This is to inform you that I am now able<lb/> to send you within 14
                days the continuation, that is<lb/> the entire manuscript of my work which I<lb/>
                intend to publish. <del>Should</del> it<add>?</add> would make me very happy if you
                not yet have chang<add>ed</add><lb/> your decision, as you told me in your recent
                    lette<add>r</add><lb/> and started with my work. But should that not<lb/> be the
                case, I ask you, to send me the manusc<add>ript</add><lb/> as soon as possible by
                express. I shall be glad to<lb/> pay for the postage. I suppose that you have<lb/>
                printed <del>my es</del> already my essays, concerning the<lb/> G E T in the
                Occident. In case you have<lb/> failed to print them, may I ask you to have
                    the<add>m</add><lb/> printed in the very next issue. I <sic>dont</sic> doubt for
                a<lb/> moment (note his psychology) that you will gra<add>nt</add><lb/> me as much
                right and justice as you gran<add>t</add><lb/>
                <persName>Levi</persName>. You can see, that in my essays I<lb/> did not
                    <del>mak</del> mention any <del>personalities</del> pers<add>?</add><lb/> though
                I possess ample material (note psycholo<add>?</add><lb/> I only discussed in detail
                the questionable<lb/> object itself. Although I <del>still</del> would have to<lb/>
                say still a whole lot in this respect,</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>however, I think that the matter is by far<lb/> finished, and a remark made at the
                proper time weig<add>?</add><lb/> more, than rash untimely expressions. As a fighter
                    f<add>or</add><lb/> Jewish truths you, as an editor really
                shoul<add>d</add><lb/> not belong to any party but should permit<lb/> anybody to
                step in the arena (to show his wits)<lb/> so that the literary (the German
                orthography, used by<lb/><persName>Kalisch</persName> is wrong, considering the time
                in which it<lb/> was written. He writes according to sound not acco<lb/> to rules)
                public may and can pass a correct<lb/> sentence and the truth may really be
                found<lb/> out. Whatever more I would have to say <add>on</add><lb/> this subject
                you will find if you think (contem/plate) at bit for yourself, and so I
                    <del>finish</del> end my let<add>ter</add><lb/> hoping that you will fulfill my
                desires as<lb/> I expressed them in this letter. Ex—<lb/>pecting your early reply, I
                am<lb/> Very truly yours<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Isidor Kalisch</persName></p>
